        "thinking": "Good, now I have the research. The key techniques:\n1. Glassmorphism with backdrop-filter blur - light, frosted\n2. Max-height smooth expansion on hover (CSS-only, fast)\n3. Minimal monochrome palette - white, gray, subtle accent\n4. Soft shadows\n5. Single centered CTA with transform\n\nNow let me redesign the banner with:\n- White/light glassmorphism\n- Opens on HOVER (pure CSS, very fast)\n- Center: single line \"▸ Analyze with AI\" \n- Light feel, not heavy\n\n\n- Collapsed to a thin 36px strip with frosted glass effect, expanding smoothly to 33vh on hover with a quarter-second transition\n- Minimal pill-style buttons for language selection and a subtle copy button, using a semi-transparent white background with backdrop blur and a delicate gray or blue-tinted border instead of heavy shadows\n- Color scheme centers on dark gray text (#374151), with optional indigo or violet accents used sparingly, and a soft shadow for depth\n\nNow I'm deciding on the interaction model—the user specifically mentioned the panel opens quickly on mouse hover, so I'm leaning toward pure CSS hover behavior where the expansion triggers immediately when the cursor enters the banner, keeping the implementation straightforward.\n\nFor the transition speed, I'll use 0.2s to match the \"very fast\" requirement. The panel itself will contain language toggle buttons in a minimal pill style, a scrollable text area for the prompt, and a copy button.\n\nI'm redesigning this to be CSS-only for the hover state while keeping JavaScript just for the language switching and copy functionality. The beauty of this approach is that hovering anywhere within the banner container keeps the panel open, so interacting with the buttons inside won't accidentally close it.\n\nBuilding the banner layout... Still writing styles...\n\nNow I'm realizing the hover approach won't work well for pushing body content down since CSS sibling selectors can't target the body element itself. I'll need to use JavaScript to adjust the body's padding when the banner expands, or create a spacer div inside the banner that grows with it. Finishing the CSS styling...\n\nThis approach works perfectly—the spacer element sits right after the banner in the DOM and expands on hover using the adjacent sibling selector, pushing all content below it down smoothly. The overall design comes together with a frosted glass strip displaying the centered trigger text, a panel that slides down to reveal the toolbar with language options and copy button, a scrollable prompt area, and the spacer handling the layout shift. I'll keep the interaction simple with just the single centered line as the hover trigger rather than adding extra hint text. Writing the banner styles... Now I'm finalizing the implementation details—I need to update the HTML structure, replace the styles in the banner section, simplify the JavaScript to only handle language switching and clipboard copying, and add proper spacing after the banner so content doesn't get hidden on hover.",
